node.text: Does your new houseplant need a new home? Transplanting them into larger pots will help them grow better, bigger, and stronger. But growth isn’t the only reason to repot: You may have a plant that looks a little sickly and in need of a nutrient boost, which it’ll get when you add new soil to its current container. Watch plant expert Katura Barnes (@terracottahotties) share her tips for repotting houseplants including what containers she loves to use and what combination of soil she prefers for her plant babies. https://bit.ly/3xUw5OC

node.text: Watch senior social media manager @ohtinapark and her mom, Mrs. Park, make kimchi at home together with their family recipe. The best part about making kimchi? It's  delicious at every stage. Whether it's served fresh alongside rice and grilled meats or after weeks of fermenting, used in a comforting stew, savory pancakes, or fried rice, homemade kimchi is the gift that keeps on giving. Learn more about the staple Korean dish here or at the link in bio: https://bit.ly/3fHCsNd #homeschoolwithmartha

node.text: Does your new houseplant need a new home? Transplanting them into larger pots will help them grow better, bigger, and stronger. But growth isn’t the only reason to repot: You may have a plant that looks a little sickly and in need of a nutrient boost, which it’ll get when you add new soil to its current container. Watch plant expert Katura Barnes (@terracottahotties) share her tips for repotting houseplants including what containers she loves to use and what combination of soil she prefers for her plant babies. https://bit.ly/3xUw5OC

node.text: Splatter painting is a fun and easy way to jazz up plain table linens (T-shirts and sneakers, too). We used Kaufman Essex Linen-Blend Fabric in Cadet and Southern Classic Linen-Blend Fabric in white as our canvases of choice. All you need is a squeeze bottle, paint, and fabric medium (to thin the contents a bit). Shake it up, then drip, drip, drip, and dry. Get the full tutorial in our July/August issue or at the link in bio. 📷: @linda.xiao created + styled by: @naomidemanana

node.text: Whether cantaloupe, honeydew, or watermelon, sweet and juicy melon is the fruit of high summer. 🍈 When the temperatures soar and the humidity is intense, melon is refreshing blended into a delicious drink. Inspired by fruity Mexican aguas frescas, these thirst quenchers are like a dip in the pool on a steamy day. The formula for each of the three recipes is the same: stir up one of our herbal simple syrups, then see what it can do with a little chopped melon, fresh citrus juice, a splash of water, and a handful of ice. Get the recipes featured in our July/August issue at the link im bio. 📷: @linda.xiao recipe + food styling by: @flossylucille prop styling by: @suzie_myers

node.text: The shells that the ocean drops at your feet during the summertime—the ones you thoroughly enjoy collecting—make lovely remembrances of the season. Encircled on a flat frame, these clamshells are naturally dyed in a gradient for a summer decoration. They’re perfect for a minimalist front-door greeting (or wall hanging) and get their ombré effect from a simple soak in dye made from purple cabbage for varying lengths of time. Get the how-to in our July/August issue or at the link in bio! 📷: @ryanliebe created by: @lornaaragon

node.text: To make grilled corn really pop, brush on one of our secret sauces: masala-lime butter or minty chili oil. Both come together with a few simple ingredients and elevate even the sweetest ears. Slather one on when the cobs are hot off the grates, and we guarantee you'll be a-maized. Get the recipe featured in our July/august issue at the link in bio. 📷: @linda.xiao recipe + food styling by: @flossylucille prop styling by: @suzie_myers

node.text: Instead of a thirsty, time-consuming lawn, Oakland-based designer @lesliecbennett of @pinehouseediblegardens and landscape architect @hollyautumnkuljian filled this front yard with a succession of easygoing flowers and perennials that morph with the seasons and "always look completely gorgeous," says homeowner Sarah Nguyen. The backyard, with its "rooms" for eating, lounging, and sitting around the firepit, is made for get-togethers. Narrower paths paved with pea gravel lead to harvest spots and clearings under mature trees, where guests can overflow. "We prefer hosting at home to eating out," Nguyen says. "It's a lot more comfortable, since many of us have young kids." Check out the full feature in our July/August issue or at the link in bio. 📷: @caitlinatkinson_photography

node.text: Capture that fleeting moment when peaches are flavor-rich and flawless with a pie that won't keep you in the kitchen.
